{
  "schema_name": "eywa_node_response",
  "schema_version": "v1",
  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "The problem requires solving a self-consistent mean-field equation for occupancy in a lattice gas model. I will delegate the derivation of the transcendental equation and the numerical root-finding.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "equation_deriver",
      "instructions": "Derive the self-consistent mean-field equation for the occupancy <n> in a lattice gas model. Use the grand canonical ensemble approach where the effective energy of a site depends on the average occupancy of its neighbors. Given the coordination numbers z_h = 4 and z_v = 8, the total coordination number z is the sum of horizontal and vertical neighbors. The energy term epsilon is given as -(k_B * T) / (2 * pi). Express the occupancy <n> as a function of mu, T, epsilon, and z in the form <n> = 1 / (1 + exp((epsilon * z * <n> - mu) / (k_B * T)))."
    },
    {
      "label": "numerical_solver",
      "instructions": "Solve the transcendental equation <n> = 1 / (1 + exp((epsilon * z * <n> - mu) / (k_B * T))) for <n>. Use the following constants: epsilon = -(k_B * T) / (2 * pi), mu = 0.1 * k_B * T, z = 12 (from z_h + z_v), and T = 300 K. Note that k_B and T will cancel out in the exponent. Find the value of <n> between 0 and 1 that satisfies the equation. Provide the result to four decimal places."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "Combine the derived mean-field equation from the first helper with the numerical solution from the second helper to provide the final occupancy value <n>."
}

